Package com.cafean.CodePlugins

Class MEPlugin

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cafean.CodePlugins.MEPlugin
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    MECodePlugin, MEFeaturePlugin
    public abstract class MEPlugin
extends java.lang.Object
    The base class for a Model Editor plugin. User defined plugins should not extend this class, but rather extend either MECodePlugin or MEFeaturePlugin.

        public void initialize()
        Performs any initialization that this plug-in requires before it is used. This method is called just after the plug-in is instantiated by the plug-in loader process.

        Implementations of this method must call super.initialize() to ensure that the base MEPlugin initializations are performed.

      • isCommandSupported

        public boolean isCommandSupported​(java.util.Vector command)
        This method returns TRUE if the current batch command should be processed by this plug-in. The default is to compare the plug-in ID to the command label.
        Parameters:

        Parameters:
        command - a Vector of Strings containing the batch command to be executed.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - on failure to process the command.

      • getVersion

        public java.lang.String getVersion()
        Returns the version number of this plugin as a String. The returned version number should be formatted as: [major].[minor].[bugfix]. For example: 1.0.2.

        This base implementation attempts to retrieve the plug-in version from the plug-in's JAR file manifest by retrieving the "MEPluginData-Version" property. Extensions of this class may choose to override this to handle version access in other ways.

        Returns:
        a String containing the version number.

      • getPluginPrereqs

        public java.lang.String[] getPluginPrereqs()
        Returns the names and versions of the plugins this plugin depends upon. Each dependency is formatted as: [plugin id]:[version] where the version is considered the minimum acceptable version.

        For example: RELAP5:0.1.0

        This base implementation attempts to retrieve the plug-in prerequisites from the "MEPluginData-RequiredPlugins" property of the plug-in's JAR file manifest as a '|' separated list of [PLUGIN]:[VERSION] as shown above. NOTE: Colons must be escaped in java manifest files, thus: "RELAP5\:0.1.0"

        Extensions of this class may choose to override this to handle prerequisite access in other ways.

        Returns:
        a String[] containing all the plugins this depends upon.

      • getPluginInfo

        public abstract java.lang.String getPluginInfo()

        Returns:
        a String containing a description of this plugin.

      • getPluginLicenseInfo

        Returns:
        a String containing license restrictions of this plugin.

      • getPluginPreferences

        Returns:
        an Object that contains the plugin's preferences.

      • getPluginHelpSet

        public javax.help.HelpSet getPluginHelpSet()
        Retrieves the HelpSet for this plug-in, if one is available. Plug-in helpsets are assumed to be located in: i18n/[locale]/[plug-in id]. For example: i18n/en/MyPlugin would refer to the english documentation for the plug-in called MyPlugin.

        Thie method will print an error message to STDERR when the debug flag is on if no help set is found in the expected location.
        The MyPlugin online help is not available. [i18n/en/MyPlugin]

        Plug-ins that place the plug-in help set in a different location may override this method to return an appropriate HelpSet.

        Returns:
        a javax.help.HelpSet properly configured for the javahelp for this plug-in.

      • getPluginHelpSets

        public java.util.List<javax.help.HelpSet> getPluginHelpSets()
        Retrieves the list of help sets for this plug-in, if one or more are available. Plug-ins may override this method to provide multiple help sets with separate names.

        This default implementation returns the HelpSet returned by getPluginHelpSet(), if one is available.

        Returns:
        the List<javax.help.HelpSet> of help sets describing this plug-in.

      • updateMainUI

        public void updateMainUI()
        This method is called during the initialization of the ApplicationFrame, and allows plug-ins to make changes to the user interface. This is primarily used to insert JToolBars into the MainToolbarManager from the ApplicationFrame.
